@node Background

                  FastPAR V1.0 Background
                  =======================


Did  you  ever try to print a TeX-document, or anything else
that's  mostly  graphics,  while  doing something else?  No?
Then you don't need this program.

But  if  you  did,  you probably noticed that printing takes
quite  a lot of CPU time, and maybe you were wondering where
all  this  CPU  time ends up.  The problem is that Commodore
tried     to    program    the    parallel.device    in    a
multitasking-friendly  way using interrupts.  But every byte
sent  to  the printer will cause any interrupt to occur, and
processing  an  interrupt  takes  a while.  So, if you print
high-resolution  graphics (lets say at 360*360 dpi), lots of
data  is  sent  to  the  printer,  lots  of  interrupts  are
generated,  and lots of time is eaten up by processing those
interrupts.

This  is  where  FastPAR  jumps  in.   FastPAR  does not use
interrupts,  but relies on polling.  Please don't scream "uh
oh, how can this guy say that polling is more efficient then
interrupts in a multitasking-environment??".  You are right,
there  is  a tradeoff.  FastPAR polls at a low priority (-5,
to be exact).  Since applications usually run at priority 0,
they  are  not  affected at all.  However, if you have a CPU
intensive  application running at a priority higher than -5,
it  will  shut  off  the  printing.   However, if you use an
editor, run a module player or do something else that is not
CPU intensive, there will be no problems.  Even if you use a
compiler, printing will continue while disk-I/O is occuring,
and of course it will resume after the compiler has finished
it's  job.   Of  course, if your printer has a large buffer,
chances   are   that  most  time-consuming-activities  won't
interrupt  printer  output.  So, you'll only get problems if
you  use a program that eats all available CPU time, such as
a raytracer at priority > -5.

Currently, FastPAR does not replace parallel.device. This
means that you can use it only with programs that
   a) don't use printer.device (i.e. programs that have
      their own printer drivers
   b) can output to a file
The program I use FastPAR with is DVIprint by Georg Heßmann,
which is part of his PasTeX package.

@endnode

